{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_bison_ver01/data/sn83045217/00295860728/1921012601/0174.xml":{"full_text":"TODAY\nTHURSDAY\nAND\nFRIDAY\n\"BURGLAR\nPROOF\"\nstarring\nn\na\u00bb\nBRYANT\npresented by\nJesse L.Lasky\nQ Q hjuu mount (picture\nNot by\ngold-dig\nStory by\nWILLIAM S. McNUTT\nDirected by\nMAURICE CAMPBELL\nScenario by\nTOM GERAGHTY\nEasy Picking?\u2014\u2014\nplugged dime! All a\nger ever got from \"Free-and-Easy\nJohn\" was cheero conversation.\nTill one ditzy night he slip\nped\u2014and the way that man split\nlucre 1!\nA PICTURE THAT OPENS\nYOUR HEART WITH A COM\nBINATION OF LAUGHS.\nWith LOIS WILSON and GRACE MORSE\n5\n1\nSEXTON ORCHESTRA OF EIGHT s\nREGULAR PRICES 3\nRAILROAD TRAFFIC\nIMPROVEMENT SEEN\nAssistant General Traffic Man\nager of Milwaukee Optimistic\nOver Situation.\nTransportation business of the rail\nroads in the west will be well started\ntoward a normal condition within 30\ndays, according to J. R. Veitch, Seattle,\nassistant general traffic manager of the\nMilwaukee railroad, who was in Great\nFalls Monday and Tuesday Conferring\nwith II. R. Wahoske, division freight\nand pafcsengor agent of the road here.\n''Indications are that railroad trans\nportation. while it will not. be entirely\nnormal, will be considerably improved\nwithin the next 30 days,\" said Mr.\nVeitdj. \"There are more inquiries on\nthe coast about lumber prices, which in\ndicates that interest in building will\nprobably be revived soon. When the\nbuilding begins prosperity will return.\n\"While there is no great volume of\nbutjness in prospect I am optimistic\n\u2022boiit the return of prosperity and be\nlief# that Spring will bring a great\nchange in business.\"\n\"LEAVES FOR EAST\nMrs. S. I. Oilman of the Cunning\nham milinery store left Monday for a\nbuying trip in the east. She will visit\nNew York, Cleveland and other eastern\ntitles.\nIf Mixed With Sulphur It Dark\nens So Naturally Nobody\nCan Tell.\nGrandmother kept her hair beauti\nfully darkened, glossy and attractive\nwith a brew of Rage Tea and Sulphur.\nWhenever her liair took on that dull,\nfaded or streaked appearance, this sim\nple mixture was applied with wonder\nful affect. By asking at any drug\nstore tor \"Wyeth's Sage and Sulphur\nCompound,\" you will get ^a large bot\ntle Of this old-time rccipe, improved\nby tha addition of other ingredients, all\nready to use, at very little cost. Thia\nsimple mixture can be depended upon\nto restore natural color and beauty to\nthe hair.\nA well-known downtown druggist\nsays everybody uses Wyeth's Sage and\nSulphur Compound now because it\ndarkens so naturally and evenly that\nnobody can teli it has been applied\nit so easy to use, too. You simply\ndampen a comb or soft hrush and\ndfi# It through your hair, taking one\nstrand at a time. By morning the\ncrag hair disappears; after another\n\u00e2fpUoatlon or two it is restored to its\n\u00c2\u00e2tttif\u00dbf. Sl h 0tt\nSTOLEN CAR FOUND\nON BOOZE HIGHWAY\nSheriff at Shelby Telephones\nMachine Is Minus Wheels\nand Equipment.\nWith all four of its wheels and much\nof its equipment missing, the Buick au\ntomobile stolen from Jack Lloyd in\nGreat Falls January 10 was found near\nShelby Tuesday by Sheriff Alsup of\nToole county, according to information\ntelephoned to Sheriff Bob Gordon. It\nwas evident to Sheriff Alsup, he stated,\nthat the car had been used by whisky\nsmugglers.\nFrequent thefts of automobiles of\none make and the appropriation of\nequipment gives rise to the belief with\nthe authorities that Whipky runners\nhave hit upon the plan of stealing cars\nand then making their identification\ndifficult by interchanging parts. The\nDuick ear of Roy Johnson of the Alca\nzar theater was found Stripped West of\nGreat Falls Inst week, several days\nafter it had been stolen, and a third\nBuiek is now mfssLng. The last car\nstolen is owned by Leon DuFresne,\n403% Central avenue.\nWill Give Shrinera\nExcursion Rates to\nDes Moines Meeting\nExcursion rates to Shriners attend\ning the annual convention of the\nNobles of the Mystic Shrine at De\u00bb\nMoines, la., June 14, 15 and 16 will\nbe granted on all railroads, according\nt<> officials of the Milwaukee and\nGreat Northern railroads here. It is\nprobable that the rates will be fare\nand a half for the round trip with the\noption of a return trip through Cali\nfornia at an additional charge of about\n$20.\nSin IS BEST\nTO CLEAR UP UGLY.\nIT\nAny breaking out or akin irritation\non face, neck or body is overcome\nquickest by applying Mentho-Sul\nphur, says a noted skin specialist.\nBecause of its germ destroying prop\nerties. nothing has ever been found\nto take the place of this sulphur\npreparation that instantly brings ease\nfrom the itching, burning and irrita\ntion.\nMentho-Rulphur heals ecaema right\nup, leaving the skin clear and smooth.\nIt seldom fails to relieve the torment\nof disfigurement. A little jar of Men\u00bb\ntho-Sulphur may be obtained at any\ndrug atore. It is used like cold cream.\nWork of Department Greater Than Ever Before\nand Organization More Efficient, Says\nMember of Commission.\nAt no time during the 'administration\nof State Highv\u00bb? Engineer John N.\nEdy hare thtre been unnecessary em\nployes in that office, according to H. A.\nTempleton of Great Falls, Secretary of\nthe executive committee of the state\nhighway commission.\nMr. Templeton's remark was in reply\nto a mention of the resolution passed\nby the legislature calling for the dis\ncharge of unnecess\u00e2ry emploies in the\nstate highway engineer's office.\n\"On the contrary,\" he declared, \"the\nwork of the department has frequently\nbeen handicapped by hating an insuffi\ncient force.\n\"Critics of the state highway depart\nment do not seem to understand that\nit takes a Considerable office and en\ngineering organization to direct more\nthan $3,000,000 Worth of work in a\nyear.\nMere Actual Work Done.\n\"More actual work, measured either\nin miles of road or dollars of Cost, has\nbeen^ done In 1920 than in the entire\nprevious life of the commission. More\nthen 600 miles o\u00a3 road in S3 counties\nhave beeft contracted at a total cost\nof more than $6.000.000. More than\nhalf Of this mileage is completed at a\ncost of more th\u00e0n $3,000,000.\n\"Word has come .to me of a report\nin Helena that of every d\u00f4i\u00ee\u00e2r spent\nby the highway commission 85 cents\nhas be An spent for engineering and of\nfice help and only 16 cents has gone\ninto the. actual construction of roads.\nThe well-meaning people who have\nspread this report have got their\nfigures twisted. The fact is that out\nof every dollar spent by the commis\nsion and its organisation in 1920, Il V&\ncents w\u00e9nt for engineering and office\nwork, and 8814 cents went into actual\nroad construction.\n\"The traveling expenses and per\ndiem accounts of the 12 members of\n$25,000 COST\nTO COUNTY OF\n1920 ELECTION\nMore Than Dollar Spent for\nEach Vote Cast, Is Showing\nby Clerk Moran.\nTwenty-five thousand dollars of the\nd'sbursements made by Cascade county\n?u 1920 was expended in meeting the\ncost of elections. County Clerk John\nE. Moran prepared a statement Tues\nday showing that the presidential pref\nerential primaries last April, the A11\nguest primaries and the November gen\neral election represented a total out\nlay of $25.004.08.\nThe total of ballots cast at the three\nelections has not been computed, tut\nthe clerk believes that each vote cost\nconsiderably more than $1.\nElection expenses were incurred in\nregistering voters, paying election\nboards, renting polling places, purchas\ning printing supplies, buying postage\nand meeting miscellaneous costs. These\nitetns in the April primaries totalled to\n$4.057, in the August primaries $ft.20S\nand in the general election $11.780.\nDetailed, the cost of the three elections\nwas as follows:\nApril primaries\u2014Registration, $400;\nelection boards, $2,026.50; printing,\n$1,147.20; re-nt, $78; postage and ex\npress, $114.18; miscellaneous. $20.40.\nAugust primaries Registration,\n$970; election boards, $3.008; print\ning, $3,025.05; rent. $115.10; postage\nand express, $018.61; miscellaneous,\n$511.14.\nGeneral election Registration,\n$1.243.75; election hoards, $5il34.70;\nprinting, $4.429.45; rent. $456.10;\npostage and express, $140.59; miscel\nlaneous, $325.42.\nThe total outlay for registering\nvoters for all elections was $2,613.75;\nelection boards, $11,129.20; printing,\n$8,602.20; rent. $049.20; postage and\nexpress. $882.38; mi\u00e0cellane\u00f4us,\n$1,127.96.\nAutomobile Show\nPlana to Be Made\nFurther plans for the annual auto\nmobile show of the Montana Automo\nbile Distributors' association at the\nHotel Rainbow March 15 to 19 will\nbe made at the regular monthly busi\nness meeting of the association next\nTuesday night, according to plans\nmade \u00e0t the noon luncheon of the or\nganization Tuesday at, the Hotel Rain\nbow. Discussion of the automobile\nshow was the main business of the\nassociation at the Tuesday noon meet\ning though a few other routine mat\nters were considered.\nTo List Excurtionists\nto Washington March 4\nH, R. Wahoske, division freight and\npassenger agent h\u00e8re for the Mil\nwaukee railroad's northern Montana\ndivision, has sent word to agents of\nthe division to get them to line up res\nervations for the special ears to leave\nChicago on March 2 for Washington\nfor the inauguration of President\nElect Harding on March 4. Reserva\ntions for the trip to Washington must\nbe made before February 25.\nRebuilds Health\nAre you fagged out, all run down\nand feel as though you could hardly\ndrag one foot after the other? If \u00abo\nyou should try a bottle of Vinol, the\ngreatest strength-building tonic.\nVINOL\nSold by Model Bx Pharmacy, Cas\ncade Rx Pharmacy, Wheeler Drug Co.,\nGreat Fftlla Drug Co.\nthe state highway commission during\n1920 Were less than $3,500.\n\"It is declared in some quarters that\nthe commission of 12 mem is unwieldy.\nMy judgment is that the criticism is\nnot well taken. Th\u00e9 body of 12 is rep\nresentative and advisory only, while the\nexecutive work is done by \u00e0 committee\nof three. I do not see, however, that\ncutting down the number of men on\nthe commission would do any harm, al\nthough I should oppose vigorously aitid\nconsider it a mistake to permit any\naction which would disrupt the oper\ntting organisation that now exists, from\nthe chief .engineer down.\n\"Montana should alio atoid the mis\ntake of creating a one-man commission,\nwith o\u00abe full-time commissioner with\nauthority over the chief engineer. The\nobviotts reason, is that such a course,\nwould put a second-rate business man\nin authority over a first-rate engineer\nand executive.\nWould Be Politloal Plan.\n\"The money paid by the state can\nnot hire a first-rate business man. Such\na course would immediately make the\nposition of a one-man state highway\ncommissioner a political plum to be\ngrabbed at by job hunters. Resolutions\npassed by the legislature, as I under\nstand them, merely instruct the chief\nengineer to discharge unnecessary em\nployes, which is not only a course he\nwould pursue under ant cireti\u00fcwtances,\nbut one he has been fouOwing,\n\"Chief Engineer John Edy Combine*\nin a most unusual degrete the qualities\nof a well-trained, practical engineer and\nan able executive. He ha\u00ab built up,\nduring the 14 months he has been on\nthe job, a Smooth rtiftbine, result-get\nting organization, and If th\u00e9 legislature\ndoes anything which will hkmper or\nupset this organisation it will do the\nstate which it seeks to serve a serious\ninjury. Mr. Edy's work speaks for it\nself; it needs no defense and will bring\nforth no apologies, from me, at least.\"\nDECLINES JOB\nASSTATEHEAD\nOF DRY LEAGUE\nBusiness Prevents H. A. Tem\npleton Serving as Anti-Saloon\nLeague President.\nPresidency of the Montana anti\nsaloou league was declined Tuesday by\nHerbert A. Templeton of Great Falls.\nMr. Templeton was elected to the po\nsition at a meeting of the league in\nHelena, January 18. In his letter to\nDr. Charles M. Donaldson of Helena,\nsecretary of the league, Mr. Temple\nton said:\n\"I regret exceedingly that I shall\nbe unable to accept this honor. The\ndemands of business on my time and\neffort are so great that I am utterly\nunable to accept any additional work\nor responsibility now.\n\"I believe the enforcement of the\nprohibition law to be one of the most\nimportant duties of th<> people at this\ntime. I say people advisedly, feeling\nthat the sentiment and active support\nof all decent people everywhere is es\nsential to success.\"\nERECT EXTERIOR\nOF NEW THEATER\nPlate Glass, Point Brick and\nTerra Cotta to Be Used\non Street Sides.\nliaying Of exterior brick on the north\nard east walls of the Liberty theatre\nbuilding. Central avenue and Third\nstreet, lias been begun and a continua\ntion of the present brand of weather\nwill permit the inclosing of the entire\nbuilding within a short time, accord\ning to N. T. Lease of the contracting\nfirm of Lease Liegland. The con\ntractors are prepared to make rapid\nprogress with the brick work, which\nwill be continued while the roof is\nbeing built. Mr. Lease stated.\nThe roof of the auditorium will be\nbuilt largely of concrete, a two inch\nslab of this material overlying the\nsteel girders, Steel joists and metal\nlath. Atop the concrete will be laid\nthe usual composition material. Plate\nglass will be used extensively in the\nsouth and west walls of the first story,\nbut above that point brick and terra\ncottn will be used e*elusively.\nMr. Lease stated that the most im\nportant work yet to be done on the\ninterior is the plastering and this can\nnot be undertaken during the winter\nuntil the heating system is in Opera\ntion. Sixty days will be required to\nfinish the plastering after it is begun\nand then the decorating crews will be\nat work for a considerable period.\nFour War Veterans\nAwarded Citizenship\nFour ex-service men of alien birth\nwere awarded the full benefits of\nAmerican cltisenstiip in district court\nTuesday after they had submitted\nproof of their military service. Rec\nommendation that they be admitted\nwas made by G. W. Tyle, naturalisation\nexaminer, who examined their creden\ntials and stated his findings to the\ncourt. The candidates were Oscar John\nLincoln of Great Falls, a native of\nEngland; Theo Carkaulis of Great\nFalls, a native of Greece; Charles A.\nHuzzas of Great Falls, a native of Rus\nsia. and James Danno of Great Falls, a\nnative of Italy.\nLewittown Rotarian\nWill Talk Thi. Noon\n1 S 1 Jg*\nPaul TVigg oftheLewlstown Rotary\nclub will talk on \"Ki Spirit ot Ro\ntary\" at the weekly luncheon meeting\nof the Great Falle Rotary club In the\npalm room of the Hotel Rainbow thie\n(Wednesday) noon.\nAbout 2,000 gallons of oil is derived\nfrom one whale of \u00abTarage sise.\nPASTORS STAND\nTO SINN FEIN\nGreat Falls Ministers Will Read\nResolutions From Pulpits\nNext Sunday.\nResolutions opposing propaganda and\nefforts to aid the so-called Irish Re\npublic, adopted at a meeting of the\nGreat F\u00e9llS Ministerial Alliance, Will\nbe read from their pulpits Sunday by\nthe 14 pastors of Protestant evangeli\ncal churches of the city.\nThe resolutions read::\n\"Whereas, much publicity and much\nactivity in behalf of the Sinn Fein and\nfho \u00abc-called Trish Republic are now In\nevidence in the United States, and\nwuere.s all Irishmen are not agreed\nor united ill their support of ihe Sinn\nFein, and especially the protestants\nof Ulster, Whose case has not been\nadequately understood in America, and\nagainst whom the Sinn Fein have de\nclared a purpose of coercion with com\npulsory submission, if necessary, to\nSinn Fein domination; and\nSay Sinn F\u00ealners Pro-German.\n\"Whereas, the Sinn Feiners during\nthe world war were pro-German and\nagainst the allies, including America;\nand according to Admiral Sims and\nother Americans, our activities were\ngreatly hampered by Irish antagonism;\nand\n\"Whereas, the present Sinn Fein\nrevolution evidently purposes to smash\nthe British Empire, the friends of civ\nilization and religious liberty through\nout the world, and are endangering our\nfriendship With the great pdWef, whose\nfriendship we should value above all\nthings in this time of world crises,\ntherefore, be it\nDisapprove Campaign In U. S.\n\"Resolved, by the. Ministerial Alli\n\u00e2hee of Great Falls, that we declare\nOur positive disapproval of the Sinn.\nFein campaign in America, and advise\"\nour people to refran from supporting\nit; we urge also our congressmen and\nsenators in Washington, and our leg\nislators in Helena, to take no action\nfavorable to the recognition of the\npresent Sinn Feifi Irish Republic or\nencourage this r\u00e9volu tionary reign of\nterror, or interfere in the affairs of\nGreat Britain in her administration of\nthis critical situation; further be it\nSo-Called Irish Republic.\n\"Res\u00f4lv\u00ead, that, since resolutions\nfavorable tft the campaign have recent\nly been published, that we pastors\nread these resolutions from our pulpits\nhext Sunday, as expressive of Our uni\nted Protestant convictions and attitude\nin regard to the Irish Question, and\nspeak upon them.\"\nResolutions were also adopted by\nthe Ministerial alliance indorsing the\nmovement on the part of the American\nlegion to consolidate the work that is\nbeing done by three agencies which\nhave undertaken to tare for wounded\nand disabled soldiers and urging Con\ngress to speedy action t oreiieve this\nsituation.\nMUSICAL COMEDY\nON P ANTAGE S BILL\nGFrls, Costumes, Singing and\nDancing Make Up Breezy\nVaudeville Kit.\n\"Lagt Night,\" featuring Earl Cavan\nough. Ann Francis. Eddie Haywood\nand a bevy of pretty girls, proved a\nbreeay musical skit with plenty of com\nedy and dancing and a little singing.\nThe stage setting was elaborate and\nthe costumes presented lots of variety,\nwhile Earl brightened up the spots\nthat would have been dull without him.\nIt was on the Pantages bill which\nopeoied Tuesday night at the Grand\ntheater.\nPaul Petching presented a real inno\nvation in his \"Musical Flower Garden,\"\nwhich gave him an opportunity to in\ntroduce a number of musical novelties.\nThe unusual lighting effects were pop\nular with the audience and the musical\nportion of the act was well received.\nCourtney and Irwin were lively in \"It\nJust Happened,\" a song and dance act\nwith a distihetly western background.\nOrvillc Stamm and his \"watchful\" bull\nterrier won lots of applause in a\n\"strong-man\" number a little out of the\nordinary. Orville sings a little and\nscatters some entertaining Comedy\nthroughout his act.\n\"The Tango Lesson\" was a little\noverdone by Wilkins and Wilkins, but\nthe pair redeemed themselves with\nsome comedy chatter. This week's bill\nIs featured by a number of stage set\ntings that are novel and elaborate.\nThe program will be repeated at the\ntwo usual performances this (Wednes\nday) evening.\nOwns Forgery Charge,\nSentenced to Prison\nOne to Three Years\nWilliam B. Nelson pleaded guilty to\na charge of forgery in district court\nTuesday and was sentenced by Judge\nH. H. Ewing to serve not less than o<tie\nnor more than three years in the state\npenitentiary. Nelson was suspected of\nIssuing fraudulent checks for a total of\n$1000. but a charge of forgery was\npreferred by County Attorney H.\nRennet in eotnnceti\u00f6h with a check for\ncashed by Andrew Thisted. In\npleading guilty Nelson admitted that\nthe check had been counterfeited with\nthe endorsement of the name of S. A.\nScott on the back.\nHANSEN ADDRESSES AD CLASS\nVacancies exist for \u00e0 few/\u00abore ex\nservice men in the advertising class at\nthe Y. M. C. A., according to Louis\nWendt, the teacher. The class was ad\ndressed Tuesday night by Charles It.\nHansen, president of the Great Faits\nAd club. It meets Tuesday and\nWednesday evenings from 7:30 to 9\no'clock.\nAttend the\n\"Ticket Dance\"\nTHURSDAY NIGHT\nJtNCW\nPrix\u00ab Spot Dance of Gold\nTable d'Hote Meala\non Milwaukee Near\nOld Price\u00bb of 1915\nla line with a policy Of bringing\nPWcM to the pre-War level as soon at\npossible, the Milwaukee railroad haa\nreduced the price of table d 'hote din\nners on its Olympian and Columbian\nfrom $1.50 to $1.25, Recording to word\nreceived by H. R. Wahoske\u00bb division\nfreight and passenger agent here. The\ntable d'hote dinner wie pat 00 in\nOlympian diners January 14 to sup\nplement the more expensive i la carte\ndinner*. The new table d 'hote dinner\nis only 25 ce\u00f9ts higher than those\nserved on the Milwaukee I\u00ab 1615.\nFORTY VACCINATED\nAT OR PHANS' HOME\nPublic Health Doctors and\nNurses Have Busy Day\nat St. Thomas.\nForty children were vaccinated\nTuesday morning at St. Thomas' or\nphanage. The Children Were all vac\ncinated last year and thoB\u00e9 vaccinated\nTuesday were newcomers since then.\nDr. Aloysius Dolan, Dr. F. T. Foard,\nMiss Dora Mecklenburg and Miss Ann\nK. Geottsche of the public health of\nfice went out to the homj to Vaccinate\nthe children.\nOnly one case of small pox has been\nreported this week in the city.\nThe epidemics of chicken pox and\nmumps are lessening, according to the\nhealth authorities. The measles seems\nto be about the same as last Week.\nCases of whooping cough are becom\ning more numerous.\nThe abnormally warm weather\nseems to be having no ill effects in\nthe city. There are not as many cases\nof cold and grippe as in the fall, the\nhealth authorities assert.\nVlounteers Put Out\nFire at Black Eagle\nin Germania Hotel\nPrompt action by the Black Eagle\nvolunteer fire department Tuesday af\nternoon placed under control a fire in\nthe Germania hotel before the trucks\nfrom the central station covered the\ndistance to the suburb. Water damage\nin thp first story Of the building was\nextensive, but had not been estimated\nTuesdar evening, it was stated by\nFire Chief A. .T. Trodick.\nThe fire originated in a pile of mat\ntresses and bedding ih the basement of\nthe hotel and Chief Trodick st\u00e0ted\nthat an investigation would be made\nbefore any statement is issued as to\nthe cause of the blaze.\nDeGorgoza Improved;\nSpends Three Weeks\nResting in Missoula\nMissoula. Jan. 25.\u2014Emilia de Gogor\nza. noted baritone singer, who Was\ntaken ill here with laryngitis three\nweeks ago. left Tuesday for San Fran\ncisco- His condition Is Improved great\nly.\nArgentine railways are furnishing\ntheir dining cars with pianos.\nNext Week Will Gould 's \"OLE\"\nTHE PALACE\nTONIGHT AND ALL WEEK\nDavid\nHarum\n.3 Aots of Comedy Drama\n2 Hours Highest Class Amusement\nGARFIELD KAST as \"DAVID\"\nYou'll Enjoy Every Minute\nSame Old Prioes\u201475c, 55c, 35o\n*one For Seats\u20140637\nNext Week Commencing Sanday\n\"OLE\"\nGfiMlTHE'ATR\nFirst Run!\nLast Times!\nWilliam Fox Presents\nThe\nShe\nTiger\nA Thrilling Drama of the\nMexican Border\nHANK MANN\n\u2014Irt\u2014\u2014\n\"THE COY COPPER'\nTwo Reels\nR\u00c4TE\nIS FAVORED BY\nRAILROAD HEADS\nMilwaukee and Great Northern\nHave Filed Proposed Cut\nWith I. C. C.\nThe One -half reduction of freight\nraten on hay to Minnesota markets\nasked of the railroads by Montana\nfarmers through state Commercial\nclubs some -time ago will probably be\ngranted almost in full, according to\nword received by officials of the\nGreat Northern arad Milwaukee rail\nroads Tuesday.\nWord was received Tuesday from\nH. II. Brown, St. faul, assistant traf\nfic manager of the Great Northern,\nby officials here that the road heads\nadvocated a rate of 42 1-2 cents a\nhundredweight on hay shipped to the\nIVin Cities, in the report to the in\nterstate commerce commission. Sub\nstantially the same are the rates ad\nvocated by the Milwaukee beads, ac\ncording to J, R. Veitch, assistant .traf\nfic manager of the Milwaukee, at Seat\ntle. The new rate will amount to\n$8.30 a ton to Minneapolis and St. Paul\ninstead of the present rate of $16 a\ntOtt. The word was the first informa\ntion for Montana farmers as to the ex\ntent of the reduction favored by the\nrailroads. While a rate of one-half the\npresent figure had becm asked by the\nfarmers, it was not believed that so\nlarge a reduction Would be granted.\nRailroad officials here expect Word\nsoon o\u00e2 the action of the interstate\ncommerce commission.\nMARRIAGE LICENSES.\nWilliam J. Thompson. 26, of Ennis,\nand Snna Jensen, 18, of Pendroy.\nHans Hill, 34, and Eilla Wuati, 35,\nboth of Lehigh.\nAllie Hanneman, 42, and Nellie\nMan Wilier, 38, both of Valier.\nPeter Falson, 52 and Flora Law\nrence, 51, both of Neihart.\nBy operating from the out\u00abide a\nnew tool for spreading automobile tire\ncasings holds them open without any\nthing being in the way of work to be\ndohe inside them.\nAL\n\"Home of 100 Per Cent Pictures\"\nLAST TIMES TODAY\n\u2014IN\u2014\nsStk\nm\n\"THE PREY\"\nStory af a Loveless Marriage\nSNUB POLLARD COMEDY\nPATHE REVIEW\nSELF SERVICE GUf\nPAY CASH\u2014 419 Central \u2014AND SAVE\nPure Fresh Creamery Butter, lb. M .46c\nStrawberries, last day at 3 cans for $1.00\nApricots, 4 large cans .$1.00\nOranges, 6 dozen for $1.00\nBananas, extra fancy, large, dozen ...50c\nBrooms, extra heavy, 4-sew, each .65c\nHoney, superior, 5-lb. pail $1.45\nJonathan Apples, extra fancy $2.10\nGrape Fruit, good size 9c up\nSapphire Flour, 98 lbs $4.65\nPAYCASH- Phone4668 -ANDSAVE\nIfectavr\nte\nThe la:\nworld Ii \u00abI\nPOSITIVELY\nLAST TIMES TODAY\nManager's Note^-Thk is a dorklog\nfood show\u2014don't Kiss it.\nAa strange as a fairy t\u00e2l*\u2014 waatha\n\u00efdventure that took Cota\u00fcie Mft*\nGill, the poor kitchen drudge, from\nher pots and pans\u2014that clothed h\u00e9r\nin silks and set' her dancing with\nher heart's desire la gilded bill\nVIOLA\nDANA\nIn Her Latest Production\nCINDERELLA'S\nTWIN\n\"Just like 'Cinderella,' youH say;\nhut not when you learn of the rob\nbery that followed\u2014the suddeb\nturmoil and the swift dosing of the\naet of the law\u2014\n'Her Beloved Burglar*\nA Fast Moving Comedy\n\"PRIZMA\"\nSomething of Color\nKernen on the Giant Organ\u2014\n\u2014Playing the Latest\nREGULAR PRICES\nAPPLES\nRed Pippins, 88 to 175,\nbox $2.50\nWinesapa, 163 to 225,\nbox $2.50\nRome Beauty, 88 to 150,\nbox $2.75\nYellow Newton, 80 to 150,\nbox $2.75\nAll wrapped and packed.\nJonathan Jumble,\nbox $1.50\nA discount of 25c On 10 bot lot\nA discount of ofl 2ft box loi.\nNo discount of Jonathan J um M\u00bb\nEvery box guarmteed fresh, firm\nand free of rot.\nWe ship any assortment desired.\nSPUDS\nRusset or Netted Gem And Rural\nNew York 11.78\n10 Sack Lots 11,15\nLet us give you quotation car\nload f. o. b. Simms, Montana.\nHAY\nKo. 1 Alfalfa, ton fSO.OO\nCan give close price oa car load\nf. o. b. Simnis.\nWe Guaranteed Everything\nSIMMS TRUCK\nGARDEN\nDaly Block\u2014 204 Fourth St. So.","height":"22920","width":"19368"}}
